        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(config): coerce whole-value ${VAR} JSON arrays/objects in env substitution",
        "body": "<!-- AI-assisted: drafted with AI assistance; evidence below is from a human-run live invocation of the config loader. -->\r\n\r\nCloses #\r\n\r\n## What Problem This Solves\r\n\r\nResolves a problem where array or object config cannot be supplied through an environment variable. Config env substitution (`resolveConfigEnvVars`) only ever returns strings, so a value written as `\"${VAR}\"` resolves to the env var's raw text. For config keys that expect an array or object (allowlists, id lists, structured limits), operators who want to keep that value out of the committed config file and inject it from the environment end up with a string where the schema expects an array/object, which fails validation. There is currently no supported way to inject a list/object config value via `${VAR}`.\r\n\r\n## Why This Change Was Made\r\n\r\nWhen a config value is **exactly one** `${VAR}` reference and the resolved text is a JSON array or object literal, it is now parsed into a real array/object. The coercion is deliberately narrow: it only applies to a sole whole-value reference (`SOLE_ENV_VAR_REFERENCE`), and only when the resolved text parses as a JSON array or object. Embedded references (`\"prefix-${VAR}\"`), multi-var strings, scalars, JSON primitives, and malformed JSON all keep their existing string result. Substitution syntax, escaping, and missing-var handling are unchanged.\r\n\r\n## User Impact\r\n\r\nOperators can inject array and object config through environment variables. For example, with `ALLOW_FROM='[\"alice\",\"bob\"]'`, a config value of `\"${ALLOW_FROM}\"` now resolves to the array `[\"alice\", \"bob\"]` instead of the string `'[\"alice\",\"bob\"]'`, so array-typed config keys validate and work as expected. Existing string substitution behavior is unaffected.\r\n\r\n## Evidence\r\n\r\nLive terminal output from running the config loader (`resolveConfigEnvVars`) from source via `node` against a real on-disk config file containing `\"allowFrom\": \"${ALLOW_FROM}\"` and `\"limits\": \"${LIMITS}\"`, with `ALLOW_FROM='[\"alice\",\"bob\"]'` and `LIMITS='{\"max\":5}'`:\r\n\r\n```\r\n{\r\n  \"channels\": { \"discord\": { \"allowFrom\": [ \"alice\", \"bob\" ] } },\r\n  \"limits\": { \"max\": 5 }\r\n}\r\nallowFrom isArray: true\r\nlimits isObject: true\r\n```\r\n\r\n`allowFrom` resolved to a real array and `limits` to a real object. Before this change the same input resolved `allowFrom` to the string `'[\"alice\",\"bob\"]'`.\r\n\r\nFocused tests (`src/config/env-substitution.test.ts`, 18 passed) cover the coercion plus passthrough for embedded references, scalars, malformed JSON, and JSON primitives. `pnpm tsgo` is clean.\r\n",
